![Image](https://www.rba.gov.au/publications/bulletin/2022/mar/images/graph-0322-6-03.svg?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

Australia’s financial system is unique because:

1. It is **highly bank-centric**
2. Mortgage transmission is **very fast** (mostly variable rate mortgages)
3. RBA uses a **floor system with Exchange Settlement (ES) balances**
4. Banks rely heavily on **wholesale funding + deposits**
5. The **liquidity ecosystem is tightly integrated with RBA operations**

We break the explanation into **four layers**, from the RBA cash rate → interbank rates → wholesale/bank funding → credit & consumption.

---

# 1. **RBA Funding Rate Framework (Cash Rate → Corridor → Surplus Liquidity)**

### **Australia uses a “corridor system” but effectively operates as a FLOOR system post-QE.**

### **Key policy rates**

* **Cash Rate Target** → main policy rate
* **Exchange Settlement (ES) balances** → reserves held at the RBA
* **Interest on ES balances** → usually **25 bps below target** (floor)
* **Repo (OMO) rate** → operational implementation

### **Mechanics**

* The RBA sets the target cash rate
* Banks trade ES balances overnight at a rate close to the target
* With huge post-QE ES liquidity, the cash rate sticks to the **floor**

**Implication:**
When the RBA hikes, **all bank funding costs immediately rise**, because ES balances reset.

**Transmission:**
**Cash Rate ↑ → Repo Rates ↑ → Bills/OIS ↑ → Bank Funding Cost ↑ → Mortgage Rates ↑**

This is *very fast* in Australia.

---

# 2. **Interbank Market Transmission (Bills, Repo, OIS)**

![Image](https://www.statista.com/graphic/1/1275329/australian-government-bonds-yields-curve.jpg?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

![Image](https://www.rba.gov.au/publications/consultations/201503-central-clearing-of-repos-in-australia/images/graph-1.gif?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

The transmission from RBA to interbank liquidity runs through 3 key markets:

---

## **2.1 Bank Bills (3M BBSW) — Australia’s LIBOR equivalent**

BBSW sets:

* Floating-rate loans
* Corporate debt pricing
* Interest rate swap (IRS) floating legs
* Wholesale bank funding spreads

**Key point:**
When the RBA tightens → BBSW rises instantly → **bank wholesale funding costs rise**.

---

## **2.2 Repo Market**

RBA uses open market ops (OMO) to:

* Drain/add liquidity
* Steer cash rate into the corridor

A tightening cycle:

* Increases general collateral (GC) repo rates
* Reduces excess ES liquidity
* Increases collateral demand (ACGBs)

**Implication for macro trades:**

* Repo specials can distort **ACGB yields**
* Elevated repo rates → tighter liquidity → benefit **receivers in swaps**

---

## **2.3 OIS Curve (Australia’s cleanest monetary expectations curve)**

AUD OIS = pure RBA expectations pricing.

Transmission:

* RBA guidance → OIS reprices instantly
* Interbank liquidity conditions → OIS volatility increases
* OIS-BBBW basis widens during stress

---

# 3. **Bank Funding Structure — Why Funding Costs Move Quickly in Australia**

Australia has a very distinct bank funding mix:

![Image](https://d2csxpduxe849s.cloudfront.net/media/469BA343-4BDA-4DA8-82EFE0F61A0F858A/A0478BFA-C964-4CD9-850D9EF37B2F443F/webimage-2B6AA4C0-6AC6-44DD-82E0A8594A8E887B.jpg?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

![Image](https://studycorgi.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/272994_1.gif?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

### **Funding Mix Breakdown (approximate)**

* **~60% deposits**
* **~20–25% wholesale funding (domestic + offshore)**
* **~10–15% securitisation (RMBS)**

### **Wholesale funding channels**

1. **Short-term wholesale funding (BBSW-linked)**
2. **Long-term bonds (5–7y typical)**
3. **Covered bonds**
4. **Offshore USD funding swapped back to AUD (cross-currency basis)**
5. **RMBS markets**

### **Transmission logic**

When RBA hikes:

1. **BBSW ↑ → bank wholesale cost ↑**
2. **Cross currency basis spreads widen** (USD funding becomes more expensive)
3. **Repo rates ↑ → collateralised borrowing costs ↑**
4. Banks pass this on through:

   * **Variable mortgage rates**
   * Business lending
   * Credit card rates

**This is why Australian rate hikes affect consumption faster than the US.**

---

# 4. **Liquidity Transmission to the Real Economy**

Australia’s mortgage market is crucial:

### **4.1 Variable-rate mortgages dominate**

* ~70% of mortgages variable or short-reset
* Rate hikes flow through nearly instantly
* Households have high debt-to-income ratios → high sensitivity to funding conditions

### **Transmission chain:**

**Cash Rate ↑ → Bank Funding Cost ↑ → Mortgage Rates ↑ → Consumption ↓ → GDP ↓**

This is **stronger and faster** in Australia than:

* US (mostly fixed mortgages)
* Canada / UK (longer reset cycles)

---

# 5. **Liquidity Conditions & Market Pricing Dynamics**

### **5.1 When liquidity tightens:**

* Repo rates spike
* Bills/OIS basis widens
* ACGB yields become more volatile
* Banks issue more term funding → pressure on long-end spreads
* AUD tends to weaken (slowing economy)

### **5.2 When liquidity is abundant:**

* ES balances flush
* Repo trades near the floor
* BBSW compresses
* OIS curve becomes smoother
* AUD can strengthen through risk sentiment

---

# 6. **Impact on Trading: FX, Rates, Credit, Curve**

## **6.1 AUD FX Trading**

Funding/liquidity dynamics affect AUD via:

* AU-US rate differentials
* Banking sector stability
* Housing transmission → growth expectations
* Risk sentiment (banks = big ASX component)

**Example:**
Higher bank funding costs → tighter credit → recession risk → **AUDJPY down**.

---

## **6.2 Rates / Curve Trades**

Funding conditions typically mean:

### **Tighter liquidity → Curve bull steepening**

Why?

* Front-end rallies (less tightening expected)
* Long-end stays anchored or cheapens due to term premia

### **Loose liquidity → Bear flattening**

* Market expects sustained growth
* RBA hikes priced in front-end

---

## **6.3 Cross-currency basis implications**

Australian banks borrow USD and swap to AUD:

* When global USD liquidity tightens → **AUD xccy basis widens (more negative)**
* This increases bank funding cost → banks hike mortgage rates → slows economy

Macro trade example:
**Long AUD 5Y5Y vs USD 5Y5Y during global easing** (because basis compresses).

---

## **6.4 Credit spreads**

Bank senior & covered spreads widen when:

* Repo markets tight
* Offshore funding expensive
* Deposits flowing out
* Cross-currency basis widening

Spreads tightening → **risk-on AUD**
Spreads widening → **risk-off AUD**

---

# 7. **Putting It Together — Australia’s Funding Liquidity Transmission Map**

### **(1) RBA Policy**

⬇
Cash Rate → OIS repricing → Repo GC rate → ES balances

### **(2) Interbank Rates**

⬇
BBSW → NCDs → Bank Bills → IRS floating leg

### **(3) Bank Funding Cost**

⬇
Deposits → Wholesale term → Covered bonds → Cross-currency basis

### **(4) Retail Borrowing Rates**

⬇
Mortgages → Business loans → Consumer credit

### **(5) Economic Activity**

⬇
Housing → Consumption → Employment → Inflation

### **(6) Market Pricing**

AUD FX → ACGB yields → Swaps → ASX200 → Credit spreads

This is why Australia has one of the **cleanest, fastest monetary transmission** frameworks in the world.

